data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with modern MSTest 3.x+ collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Before (`Assert.IsTrue`) | After (specialized) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clear failure: "expected non-empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows expected vs actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | Remove — `Single()` already throws if missing | Redundant check |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` predicate check is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API.

Also consider sealing the test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance per MSTest best practices.
